  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is it legal to work remotely on a B211A visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Gray area. The B211A is technically for social/business visits, not work. The dedicated Remote Worker visa exists but has $60k income requirements. In practice, thousands of nomads work remotely on B211A without issues.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I pay Indonesian taxes?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you stay 183+ days per year, you may become a tax resident. Most nomads track their days and do visa runs or leave before hitting the threshold. Consult a tax professional for your situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay in Indonesia?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          With B211A and extensions, theoretically indefinitely. Each extension is 60 days. Some nomads have been in Bali for years this way. The Second Home Visa offers 5-10 years for those with savings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How reliable is the internet?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Variable. Canggu and Seminyak have decent fiber in many villas. Coworking spaces are reliable. Outages happen. Many nomads use Starlink or mobile hotspot backup for important calls.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I use a visa agent?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For B211A, yes. Agents provide the required sponsor, handle paperwork, and manage extensions. It's $50-200 for significant convenience. Ask for recommendations in Bali nomad groups.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Bali safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Generally yes. Petty theft exists (secure belongings on motorbikes). Traffic is the main danger—motorbike accidents are extremely common. The biggest health risks are dengue and contaminated water/food.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

